3 Univariate Graphs¶

In [ ]:
plt.hist(df["YearBuilt"], bins = 10)
plt.xlabel("Year Built")
plt.ylabel("Count")
plt.title("Frequency of Properies in the Year Built")
plt.show()

The first graph is a histogram with the independent variable being the year the property was built and the response variable being the count of buildings from that year range. With a bin size set to 10, each bin holds years roughly in a 12 year range. Based on this plot, most of the properties were built in the last 60 years, around the 1960's. Strangely, there are very few properties built around the late 1930's to 1950's. Through pure speculation, this may be due to the World Wars at the time. Despite the higher volume of properties in the later half of the plot, there are still a considerable number of properties prior to th2 1950's. This means that when building our model, we will know that the distribution of data points in YearBuilt is somewhat balanced.

In [ ]:
df["BuildingType"].value_counts().plot(kind = "barh", xlabel="Count", title="Frequency of Building Types")
Out[ ]:
<Axes: title={'center': 'Frequency of Building Types'}, xlabel='Count', ylabel='BuildingType'>

The second graph is a bar chart where the independent variable is the building type and the response is the count of properties of that type. This information is valuable to distinguish what the majority of our data's purpose is. Whether the building is meant for residential living or office spaces can be an interesting factor to consider when making our model. It can also tell us that our model will be better suited to predict data points that are classified under Multifamily HR, MR, or nonresidential as those are the most dominant categories of building types.

In [ ]:
# total GHG emissions divided by properties total gross floor area
# measured in kilograms of carbon dioxide equivalent per square foot.

Q1 = df["GHGEmissionsIntensity"].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = df["GHGEmissionsIntensity"].quantile(0.75)

outlier_boundary = Q3 + (1.5*(Q3-Q1))

fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2)

df["GHGEmissionsIntensity"].plot(kind='box', ax=axes[0], ylabel="kg of CO2 per square foot")
axes[0].set_title("GHG Emissions Intensity")

df.loc[df["GHGEmissionsIntensity"] <= outlier_boundary, "GHGEmissionsIntensity"].plot(kind='box', ax=axes[1])
axes[1].set_title("GHG Emissions Intensity (removed outliers)")

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

The last univariate graph is a box plot showing the spread of property's greenhouse gas emission intensity which is the total green house gas emitted divided by the total gross floor area. The units are then kilograms of carbon dioxide per square foot. In the plot to the left, the raw data is shown to have heavy outliers that skew the box plot far to the higher range of GHG intensity. When removing these outliers using the 1.5 IQR rule, the plot becomes the one on the right. It is sill heavily skewed, but despite this, we can say that 50% of our data points have a GHG intensity range of roughly 0.2 to 0.9. This is impressive as the average intensity of an office spaces is 8.6 kg/sq ft (see link). This tells us that although this dataset is heavily skewed in terms of GHG emission intensity, Seattle appears to have a far less intensity as compared to other parts of the US.

https://www.cnaught.com/blog/carbon-calculator-methodology#:~:text=Office%20space,individuals%20using%20the%20office%20space.

The first bivariate graph shows the count of EPA property types within each type of building. EPA property type is the property's primary use defined by a function that accounts for more than 50% of a property. Unfortunately, because there are 64 distinct property types, the color contrast and identification is harder to tell. This tells us that we will probably want to alter the EPAPropertyType feature to combine several types into an "other" or "misc" classification of in order to cut down on the large number property types. Regardless, this current graph shows us that a large portion of the nonresidential buildings are classified as offices. The two that appear to be tied for second are non-refrigerated warehouses and mixed use properties.

In [ ]:
df.plot(kind="scatter", alpha = 0.25, x = "YearBuilt", y = "ENERGYSTARScore", title = "Property's Year Built VS ENERGY STAR Score")
Out[ ]:
<Axes: title={'center': "Property's Year Built VS ENERGY STAR Score"}, xlabel='YearBuilt', ylabel='ENERGYSTARScore'>

The second bivariate plot is a scatter plot with the year the property was built as the x-axis and the ENERGY STAR score as the y-axis. Here it can be seen that most of the data falls above an ENERGY STAR score of 70. Since the ENERGY STAR score is the percentile of the property's performance, most of the properties in Seattle perform better than 70% of all properties ENERGY STAR has queried from. Additionally, there appears to be less poor performing properties (score of less than 30) in the years of 1990-2022 compared to 1950-1980. This is evidence that our hypothesis that more recent buildings are more energy efficient seems to hold some truth.

The third bivariate plot is a boxplot of GHG emission intensity grouped by building type. In the first plot, there are no outliers removed. Because of this, it is clear that two Non-residential WA properties have extremely large GHG emission intensity. When removing some of the outliers (anything equal to or greater than 10), the second plot shows some more nuance. Nonresidential and Multifamily LR & MR both are heavily skewed towards the high end of emissions intensity, which makes sense as most of our data comes from these three categories. Also, it seems that nonresidential COS (City of Seattle) properties have the highest median intensity while Multifamily LR properties have the lowest.

# slicing dataframe to zoom in on the graph

new_df = df.loc[(df["SourceEUI(kBtu/sf)"] < 1000) & (df["PropertyGFATotal"] <1000000)]

colors = ['#d3d3d3', '#d2691e', '#006400', '#ff0000', '#ffd700', '#00ff00', '#0000ff', '#ff1493']
fig, ax = plt.subplots()

for i, (buildingType, group) in enumerate(new_df.groupby("BuildingType")):
    group.plot(kind="scatter", x="PropertyGFATotal", y="SourceEUI(kBtu/sf)", alpha=0.3, label=buildingType, color=colors[i % len(colors)], ax=ax)

plt.legend(title="Building Type")
plt.xlabel("Property Gross Floor Area Total")
plt.ylabel("Source Energy Use Intensity (kBtu/sf)")
plt.title("Source EUI vs Property GFA Total, Grouped by Property Type")
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left', title="Building Type")
plt.show()

The first high dimensional graph is a scatter plot between a property's total gross floor area and their source energy use intensity (annual energy used to operate divided by gross floor area) color-coded by the building type. Because there are many outliers that stretch the graph of its readability, the second plot has sliced down the dataset so as to "zoom in" on the majority of the data. At this level, it appears that for nonresidential properties, a higher total gross floor area does not increase source energy use intensity; the yellow points begin vertically spread in the lower ranges of area (although more heavily concentrated in lower intensity), but become more sparse and tend towards lower sourse energy use intensity. Overall, this graph suggests that larger gross floor areas will have a lower energy use intensity.

Much like the previous graph against energy use intensity, a higher gross floor area seems to have lower GHG emission intensity. These two high dimensional graphs might be evidence that larger properties consume more energy overall, they are porportionally more energy efficient and less polluting than smaller properties.

2 Additional Graphs Highlighting Problems¶

Out[ ]:
<Axes: title={'center': 'Frequency of Property Types'}, xlabel='Count', ylabel='EPAPropertyType'>

This extra graph is the count of all EPA property types. It highlights the imbalance of classified property types in our dataset. This graph will be useful when deciding which classifications to group together as a general "other" category to reduce the 64 types. By combining groups to larger classes, our model will be able to more accurately generalize predictions as there will be more data in each new category.

In [ ]:
#SourceEUI(kBtu/sf)
# Source Energy Use Intensity (EUI) is a property's Source Energy Use divided by its gross floor area. 
# Source Energy Use is the annual energy used to operate the property, including losses from generation, transmission, & distribution. 
# Source EUI is measured in thousands of British thermal units (kBtu) per square foot.

# SourceEUIWN(kBtu/sf)
#Weather Normalized (WN) Source Energy Use Intensity (EUI) is a property's WN Source Energy divided by its gross floor area. 
#WN Source Energy is the Source Energy Use the property would have consumed during 30-year average weather conditions. 
#WN Source EUI is measured in measured in thousands of British thermal units (kBtu) per square foot.

df.loc[df["SourceEUI(kBtu/sf)"] < 2000,].plot(kind = "scatter", x = "SourceEUIWN(kBtu/sf)",y = "SourceEUI(kBtu/sf)", alpha = 0.2, xlabel= "Weather Normalized Souce Energy Use Intensity", ylabel = "Souce Energy Intensity", title = "SourceEUIWN VS SourceEUI")
Out[ ]:
<Axes: title={'center': 'SourceEUIWN VS SourceEUI'}, xlabel='Weather Normalized Souce Energy Use Intensity', ylabel='Souce Energy Intensity'>

This scatter plot shows the relationship between SourceEUIWN(kBtu/sf), which is the source energy intensity of a property over a would-be 30 year average weather conditions, and source energy intensity. This relationship is so linear, that it is possible that these values are dupliates or so close to each other that we can neglect one of them to keep our dataset less redundant. It may also suggest that simply the annual source energy intensity is enough to average the next 30 years worth of energy use intensity given average weather conditions.
